      Musk v. Twitter
   =20
 =20

A month ago, Elon Musk=E2=80=99s fight with Twitter Inc. was a merger dispu=
te. Musk signed a merger agreement with Twitter in April, in which he agree=
d to buy Twitter for about $44 billion. Then the stock market went down, an=
d Musk decided that he didn=E2=80=99t want to pay $44 billion for Twitter a=
nymore. And so, like lots of  other regretful acquirers before him, he trie=
d to find an excuse to get out of the deal. There is a standard set of ways=
 to do this. The merger agreement is 73 pages long, full of representations=
 and covenants and conditions. You read through the merger agreement, you f=
ind some places where you think Twitter has not lived up to its obligations=
 or met its conditions, you send Twitter a letter saying that and terminati=
ng the deal, Twitter sues you, and you meet up in Delaware Chancery Court t=
o argue over what the merger agreement requires.
This is in fact what Musk did. Frankly  I did not think that he did a very =
good job of it. His main excuse is that the merger agreement contained a re=
presentation that no more than 5% of Twitter=E2=80=99s monetizable daily ac=
tive users are spam or bot accounts, but in fact vastly more than 5% are bo=
ts, so he can get out of the deal. No part of this excuse is true in any wa=
y: The merger agreement does=C2=A0not=C2=A0contain that representation, the=
re is no evidence that it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0wrong, and even if it existed and =
was wrong it would not be a reason to get out of the deal unless it caused =
a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D on Twitter=E2=80=99s business, =
which seems unlikely. Nonetheless, this is how you play the game.=C2=A0Musk=
 is trying to prove that the merger agreement does=C2=A0not require him to =
buy Twitter; Twitter is trying to prove that it does. Like most observers, =
I think that it clearly does, so this is an uphill fight for Musk, but you =
never know.
There is, however, another approach. Imagine that the merger agreement was =
not 73 pages; imagine it was only a single sentence. =E2=80=9CElon Musk wil=
l pay $44 billion in cash on Oct. 31, to buy Twitter Inc., no matter what, =
with absolutely no conditions.=E2=80=9D Then I think everyone would agree t=
hat the merger agreement requires him to buy Twitter. But then imagine that=
 it turned out that Twitter was an entirely fake company: It had no revenue=
, sold no ads, made no money, had no users (except Elon Musk?); it was just=
 a long-running fiction that a handful of Twitter executives used to trick =
shareholders into giving them money, and their plan to exit the scam was to=
 sell the whole thing to Musk. Imagine the truth came out =E2=80=94=C2=A0pe=
rhaps there=E2=80=99s a whistle-blower =E2=80=94=C2=A0between signing and c=
losing. Would Musk have to close the deal? According to the language of the=
 contract, sure, yeah, =E2=80=9Cno matter what.=E2=80=9D But the real answe=
r is no. Musk could get out of the contract, not under the terms of the con=
tract, but because Twitter got him to sign the contract via=C2=A0fraud. And=
 he could go to court, claiming fraud and demanding =E2=80=9Crescission=E2=
=80=9D (tearing up the contract), and =E2=80=94=C2=A0in this imaginary scen=
ario =E2=80=94=C2=A0the court would probably agree with him.
Obviously that=E2=80=99s not what happened, but I suppose you could tell a =
story that=C2=A0something like that=C2=A0happened. The story would be: =E2=
=80=9CTwitter goes around saying that fewer than 5% of its mDAUs are bots, =
but that is a lie, and Musk was deceived by that lie, so he signed the merg=
er agreement, so he was defrauded and can get out of it,=C2=A0regardless of=
 what the merger agreement says.=E2=80=9D And in fact that is part of Musk=
=E2=80=99s defense (technically, his first counterclaim
  [1]
) to Twitter=E2=80=99s lawsuit: Even if he has to close the merger under th=
e terms of the merger agreement, that doesn=E2=80=99t matter, because he wa=
s tricked into signing the merger agreement by Twitter=E2=80=99s fraud.
I am not very impressed by this theory=C2=A0either. For one thing, it has n=
o evidence that Twitter did any fraud at all; Musk=E2=80=99s complaints abo=
ut the bots are completely made up. For another thing, proving fraud requir=
es proving a certain state of mind on both sides. Twitter didn=E2=80=99t co=
mmit fraud unless it had some=C2=A0intent=C2=A0to deceive; an innocent good=
-faith error about bot-counting might be enough to breach the merger agreem=
ent (it isn=E2=80=99t) but you=E2=80=99d need to prove an intentional lie t=
o prove fraud. And Musk can=E2=80=99t claim fraud unless he=C2=A0relied=C2=
=A0on the fraud; he has to demonstrate that he believed Twitter about the b=
ots and that that=E2=80=99s part of the reason he signed the deal,  which o=
bviously isn=E2=80=99t true. In fact, before the deal, he went around compl=
aining about how Twitter had too many bots and how he was going to clean it=
 up, so it is silly for him to now claim that he only signed the deal becau=
se he was tricked into thinking there were no bots.
But, you know, you try a bit of everything, why not.
And then last week a Twitter whistle-blower appeared: Peiter =E2=80=9CMudge=
=E2=80=9D Zatko, a former security executive at Twitter, went public claimi=
ng that Twitter was doing various bad security things in fraudulent ways, b=
eing cavalier with user data and violating agreements with the Federal Trad=
e Commission and concealing information from its board of directors.
We talked about this last week, and  I noted that Zatko confirms that Twitt=
er is right and Musk is wrong about their central contractual dispute: Zatk=
o agrees with Twitter=E2=80=99s estimates that fewer than 5% of its mDAUs a=
re spam bots; he just thinks that Twitter should be doing a better job of f=
ighting spam accounts that it=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0count as mDAUs.
But the broader point is that Zatko=E2=80=99s claims can help Musk, because=
 he alleges intentional fraud=C2=A0at Twitter that Musk=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0know about. The schematic form of Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint is (1) Tw=
itter was doing very bad security practices, (2) those practices created po=
tentially disastrous risks (of legal liability, of lost business, of regula=
tory fines, etc.) for Twitter,=C2=A0(3) Twitter was lying to the public abo=
ut those risks, and (4)=C2=A0its executives were doing that intentionally i=
n order to keep their jobs and bonuses. =E2=80=9CNever mind the stuff about=
 the bots,=E2=80=9D Musk could argue; =E2=80=9CI was tricked into buying th=
is company that was just a crater of liability because they were lying abou=
t their security practices.=E2=80=9D
This is potentially a better argument than the stuff about the bots, becaus=
e:
=09The claims come from a respected hacker who was an executive at Twitter =
and ought to know, whereas the bot stuff is just something that Musk made u=
p with no evidence.=09It sounds bad? =E2=80=9CMudge Discovers Egregious Def=
iciencies, Negligence, Willful Ignorance, and Threats to National Security =
& Democracy,=E2=80=9D is a section header in Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint. If =
you want to get out of a deal because Twitter hid bad stuff from you, =E2=
=80=9CThreats to National Security=E2=80=9D does sound like bad stuff.=09Mu=
sk=C2=A0can=C2=A0say he relied on it. One problem with Musk=E2=80=99s claim=
s about the bots is that Musk went around=C2=A0before the deal complaining =
about how Twitter had too many bots and how he was the one to get rid of th=
