This  article is from Saturday, though it could be from any time in the las=
t five years:

Take Tether, the company behind the world=E2=80=99s largest stablecoin. In =
recent months, it launched a marketing blitz of blogs and press releases, t=
outing its transparency, after a series of crypto firm failures rattled inv=
estor confidence in it. Tether is designed to grease the rails of the rough=
ly $1 trillion cryptocurrency market by promising each token can be redeeme=
d for $1. Market observers have long questioned whether the firm=E2=80=99s =
reserves are sufficient and have been demanding audited information.
The company has been promising an audit since at least 2017. An audit is =
=E2=80=9Clikely months=E2=80=9D away, said Paolo Ardoino, chief technology =
officer of Tether Holdings which issues the tether coin that recently carri=
ed a market value of $68 billion.
=E2=80=9CThings are going slower than=E2=80=A6we would like,=E2=80=9D Mr. A=
rdoino said.

The basic situation with Tether is that it claims to be 100% backed by safe=
 assets. Actually it claims to be about 100.3% backed: For every $1 of Teth=
er outstanding, there are about $1.003=C2=A0of assets that Tether keeps in =
a box.
  [2]
 But Tether is notoriously secretive about what it keeps in the box. Wherea=
s a typical money-market fund will   list the exact dollar amount and CUSIP=
=C2=A0of every instrument that it owns, Tether discloses broad categories o=
f securities; whereas banks and money-market funds have audited accounts, T=
ether is perpetually months away from the audit that will finally solve all=
 of its problems.
And plainly Tether is=C2=A0not always=C2=A0100%, or 100.3%,=C2=A0backed by =
very safe assets. For one thing, even its  current =E2=80=9Creserves breakd=
own,=E2=80=9D as of June 30, 2022, says that 8.36% of its assets are in =E2=
=80=9COther Investments (Including Digital Tokens),=E2=80=9D and digital to=
kens sometimes lose value. If Tether=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cother investments=
=E2=80=9D lost 10% of their value, then Tether would no longer be fully bac=
ked: Each Tether=C2=A0was=C2=A0backed by $1.003 of assets, but if 8% of its=
 portfolio lost 10% of its value then it would=C2=A0be backed by only $0.99=
5 of value. Cryptocurrencies lose 10% of their value all the time. Also the=
re is some historical record of Tether counting risky loans =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
to   its affiliate Bitfinex, to  busted crypto lender Celsius=C2=A0=E2=80=
=94=C2=A0as part of its assets. So far=C2=A0those loans seem to have been p=
aid back in full, so it=E2=80=99s fine I guess, but with just a 0.3% equity=
 cushion there is not much margin for error.
The interesting question with Tether is: Let=E2=80=99s say that you=C2=A0kn=
ew, definitively, that Tether =E2=80=9Cbroke the buck.=E2=80=9D Some of its=
 not-so-safe assets didn=E2=80=99t pan out, and each Tether turned out to o=
nly be backed by, say, 97 or 98 cents of assets. In the world of  money-mar=
ket funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0or of regulated=C2=A0banks=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0tha=
t would be a disaster; that would be insolvency and a bank run and the end =
of the fund and a possible systemic crisis. Investors put their dollar in e=
xpecting that they could always get exactly $1 back, and if they find out t=
hat they can=E2=80=99t then they=E2=80=99ll race to get their $1 while they=
 still can, and the fund will be forced to liquidate its holdings and furth=
er drive down their prices and leave investors with big losses that they we=
re not expecting.
In the world of stablecoins =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know? It is not =
obvious that the same intuitions apply. The point of a stablecoin is not=C2=
=A0mainly=C2=A0to be a secure claim on $1 of assets in a bank account. The =
point of a stablecoin is mainly =E2=80=9Cto grease the rails of the roughly=
 $1 trillion cryptocurrency market,=E2=80=9D by being the on-blockchain for=
m of a dollar. We   talk somewhat frequently about stablecoins that are=C2=
=A0openly=C2=A0backed by nothing but overcomplicated confidence in their ow=
n value; to be fair, we mostly talk about them when they are crashing to ze=
ro, but still. The thing that makes a stablecoin worth a dollar is=C2=A0pri=
marily=C2=A0that big crypto investors treat it as being worth a dollar, tha=
t they use it as a medium of exchange and a form of collateral and value it=
 at $1 for those uses. Being backed by $1.003 of dollar-denominated safe as=
sets=C2=A0helps=C2=A0with that, but being backed by $0.98 of dollar-denomin=
ated assets might be good enough?
One way of putting this might be that Tether is =E2=80=9Ctoo big to fail,=
=E2=80=9D that the people who use it have incentives to continue treating i=
t as being worth $1 even if it never to gets around to proving that it has =
assets worth $1 per Tether.
  [3]
 Another way of putting it is that people don=E2=80=99t worry too much abou=
t the =E2=80=9Cbacking=E2=80=9D of the US dollar itself; a dollar buys a ce=
rtain amount of goods and services because of broad social acceptance rathe=
r than any reserve of gold in a vault somewhere. If enough people believe t=
hat a Tether just is a dollar in the crypto world, maybe that=E2=80=99s eno=
ugh to make it true.

