We   talked on Thursday about a paper titled =E2=80=9CThe =E2=80=98Actual R=
etail Price=E2=80=99 of Equity Trades,=E2=80=9D by Christopher Schwarz, Bra=
d Barber, Xing Huang, Philippe Jorion and Terrance Odean. The paper finds t=
hat different retail brokerages execute orders for the same amount of the s=
ame stock at the same time at=C2=A0different prices, and that some brokers =
consistently provide better prices than others. But this is not correlated =
with how much payment for order flow each broker receives: Some brokers tha=
t accept lots of payment for order flow do better than some brokers who acc=
ept none, and vice versa.
Which leaves a mystery. These brokers send their customers=E2=80=99 orders =
to wholesalers, electronic market-makers that compete to fill the orders. T=
he wholesalers systematically give better execution=C2=A0prices to some bro=
kers than others, but it has nothing to do with how much they are paying th=
ose brokers for those orders. But the professors don=E2=80=99t explain what=
 does cause the difference.
The explanation that I proposed on Thursday was basically: Different retail=
 brokers have different sorts of customers, and those different customer ba=
ses might be more or less profitable for market-makers. A retail brokerage =
whose customers are semiprofessional, who make relatively informed=C2=A0tra=
des in relatively large size, will be less profitable for a market maker th=
an one whose customers put in small random orders. So a market maker who no=
tices that one brokerage has smarter bigger orders will charge that brokera=
ge=E2=80=99s customers more (offer them less price improvement) than a brok=
erage with dumber smaller orders. The best-performing brokerage, on this me=
asure, will be the one with the worst-performing=C2=A0customers.
I like this explanation, because I think it is initially surprising yet=C2=
=A0pleasingly intuitive, and also probably true. There is a prior literatur=
e. In 2001, Robert Battalio, Robert Jennings and Jamie Selway published a p=
aper finding that =E2=80=9Cbroker identity may allow market makers to diffe=
rentiate between customers when pricing market-making services,=E2=80=9D be=
cause, effectively, some retail brokers=E2=80=99 customer bases are better =
at trading than others=E2=80=99. If you are buying order flow from good tra=
ders, you should charge higher spreads than you charge the=C2=A0bad traders=
.
That said, a couple of people emailed and  tweeted a different proposed=C2=
=A0explanation for the result in the paper.
  [4]
=C2=A0Here, the professors sent orders to buy $100 worth of stock simultane=
ously to five different retail brokers (six, if you consider their two diff=
erent Interactive Brokers accounts separately), and they systematically got=
 different results, with some brokers regularly getting better executions t=
han others. You could tell a story like:
=09They put these orders in more or less simultaneously (using the applicat=
ion programming interfaces at each brokerage, or pressing the buttons on th=
e brokerage=E2=80=99s website).=09The brokerages then took different amount=
s of time to process these orders and send them to market makers: Some brok=
erages have slower APIs, slower websites, slower routers, more complicated =
order-checking procedures, etc., so they take longer to send their orders t=
o market makers.=09So the market makers systematically=C2=A0receive=C2=A0or=
ders from Brokerage A first, then Brokerage B, then Brokerage C, etc., if y=
ou put the orders in all at the same time.=09In general, when a market make=
r gets an order to buy $100 of a stock, it will fill it at the best availab=
le price. If it gets another order to buy $100 of the same stock a millisec=
ond later, it will fill it at a slightly worse price: In general, prices=C2=
=A0move=C2=A0in response to demand, and as more orders come in to buy the s=
ame stock the price will go up.
  [5]
=C2=A0=09Because the professors are sending six separate orders to buy the =
same stock at almost the same time, the first to execute will always get th=
e best price and the last will get the worst.=09If true, this=C2=A0is=C2=A0=
a sort of evaluation of the brokerages=E2=80=99 performance: The =E2=80=9Cb=
est=E2=80=9D one does execute orders a bit faster than the =E2=80=9Cworst=
=E2=80=9D one.=09But it doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0matter=C2=A0to any actual reta=
il investors: In general, you are not sending six separate orders on six se=
parate platforms, so this doesn=E2=80=99t affect you. Tiny differences in l=
atency among platforms don=E2=80=99t matter if no one else is racing you=C2=
=A0to send orders at the exact same time, and if you are a normal retail in=
vestor they absolutely aren=E2=80=99t.
  [6]



I don=E2=80=99t think this is the explanation, and the authors explicitly r=
eject it:
Given the importance of latency on our results, we examine the submission t=
ime differences as well as the execution time differences of our trades for=
 each broker pair. Table AII in Appendix A describes the distributions of d=
ifferences in submission and execution times for=C2=A0pairs of brokers. Eac=
h broker pair has trades in almost perfectly random order. Most of the trad=
es are within one second of each other. Also, the median execution time dif=
ferences are essentially zero. Thus, no broker has any systematic advantage=
 in terms of submission and execution times.
But I mention it here because several people proposed it, and it=E2=80=99s =
interesting.

