10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Musk v. Twitter</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A month ago, Elon Musk=E2=80=99s fight with Tw=
itter Inc. was a merger dispute. Musk signed a merger agreement with Twitte=
r in April, in which he agreed to buy Twitter for about $44 billion. Then t=
he stock market went down, and Musk decided that he didn=E2=80=99t want to =
pay $44 billion for Twitter anymore. And so, like lots of <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMTIvaS13YXMtdG9sZC10aGVyZS=
1kLWJlLWEtY2FrZS1tZXJnZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDgyOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1b=
T1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwODI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWln=
bj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB491ac5c6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> other regretfu=
l acquirers</a> before him, he tried to find an excuse to get out of the de=
al. There is a standard set of ways to do this. The <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvd=
i9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTgwOTEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMTIwNDYxL2QzMTA4NDNk=
ZXgyMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaaf8d937" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">merger agreement</a>=
 is 73 pages long, full of representations and covenants and conditions. Yo=
u read through the merger agreement, you find some places where you think T=
witter has not lived up to its obligations or met its conditions, you send =
Twitter a letter saying that and terminating the deal, Twitter sues you, an=
d you meet up in Delaware Chancery Court to argue over what the merger agre=
ement requires.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is in fact what Musk did. Frankly <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMTgvZWxvbi13YW50=
cy10by1maWdodC10aGUtYm90cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwODI5MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXV=
tPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA4MjkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaW=
duPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB37ad4de2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I did not thi=
nk</a> that he did a very good job of it. His main excuse is that the merge=
r agreement contained a representation that no more than 5% of Twitter=E2=
=80=99s monetizable daily active users are spam or bot accounts, but in fac=
t vastly more than 5% are bots, so he can get out of the deal. No part of t=
his excuse is true in any way: The merger agreement does=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0=
</em>contain that representation, there is no evidence that it=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0wrong, and even if it existed and was wrong it would not be a reason to =
get out of the deal unless it caused a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=
=80=9D on Twitter=E2=80=99s business, which seems unlikely. Nonetheless, th=
is is how you play the game.=C2=A0Musk is trying to prove that the merger a=
greement does=C2=A0<em>not </em>require him to buy Twitter; Twitter is tryi=
ng to prove that it does. Like most observers, I think that it clearly does=
, so this is an uphill fight for Musk, but you never know.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is, however, another approach. Imagine t=
hat the merger agreement was not 73 pages; imagine it was only a single sen=
tence. =E2=80=9CElon Musk will pay $44 billion in cash on Oct. 31, to buy T=
witter Inc., no matter what, with absolutely no conditions.=E2=80=9D Then I=
 think everyone would agree that the merger agreement requires him to buy T=
witter. But then imagine that it turned out that Twitter was an entirely fa=
ke company: It had no revenue, sold no ads, made no money, had no users (ex=
cept Elon Musk?); it was just a long-running fiction that a handful of Twit=
ter executives used to trick shareholders into giving them money, and their=
 plan to exit the scam was to sell the whole thing to Musk. Imagine the tru=
th came out =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps there=E2=80=99s a whistle-blower =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0between signing and closing. Would Musk have to close the deal? Ac=
cording to the language of the contract, sure, yeah, =E2=80=9Cno matter wha=
t.=E2=80=9D But the real answer is no. Musk could get out of the contract, =
not under the terms of the contract, but because Twitter got him to sign th=
e contract via=C2=A0<em>fraud</em>. And he could go to court, claiming frau=
d and demanding =E2=80=9Crescission=E2=80=9D (tearing up the contract), and=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0in this imaginary scenario =E2=80=94=C2=A0the court would p=
robably agree with him.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously that=E2=80=99s not what happened, bu=
t I suppose you could tell a story that=C2=A0<em>something like that=C2=A0<=
/em>happened. The story would be: =E2=80=9CTwitter goes around saying that =
fewer than 5% of its mDAUs are bots, but that is a lie, and Musk was deceiv=
ed by that lie, so he signed the merger agreement, so he was defrauded and =
can get out of it,=C2=A0<em>regardless of what the merger agreement says</e=
m>.=E2=80=9D And in fact that is part of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3JwZ292Lmxhdy5oYXJ2YXJk=
LmVkdS8yMDIyLzA4LzEwL3R3aXR0ZXItdi1tdXNrLXBsYWludGlmZnMtcmVzcG9uc2UtdG8tZGV=
mZW5kYW50cy1jb3VudGVyY2xhaW0v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7a71d608" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
Musk=E2=80=99s defense</a> (technically, his first counterclaim<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>) to Twitter=E2=80=99s lawsuit: Even if he has to close the merger unde=
r the terms of the merger agreement, that doesn=E2=80=99t matter, because h=
e was tricked into signing the merger agreement by Twitter=E2=80=99s fraud.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not very impressed by this theory=C2=A0ei=
ther. For one thing, it has no evidence that Twitter did any fraud at all; =
Musk=E2=80=99s complaints about the bots are completely made up. For anothe=
r thing, proving fraud requires proving a certain state of mind on both sid=
es. Twitter didn=E2=80=99t commit fraud unless it had some=C2=A0<em>intent=
=C2=A0</em>to deceive; an innocent good-faith error about bot-counting migh=
t be enough to breach the merger agreement (it isn=E2=80=99t) but you=E2=80=
=99d need to prove an intentional lie to prove fraud. And Musk can=E2=80=99=
t claim fraud unless he=C2=A0<em>relied=C2=A0</em>on the fraud; he has to d=
emonstrate that he believed Twitter about the bots and that that=E2=80=99s =
part of the reason he signed the deal, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTcvZWxvbi1tdXNrLWRvZXMtbm90LWNhcmUtYWJvdXQtc=
3BhbS1ib3RzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRt=
X3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDgyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHV=
mZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf1fec863" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> which obviously isn=E2=80=
=99t true</a>. In fact, before the deal, he went around complaining about h=
ow Twitter had too many bots and how he was going to clean it up, so it is =
silly for him to now claim that he only signed the deal because he was tric=
ked into thinking there were no bots.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, you know, you try a bit of everything, wh=
y not.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then last week a Twitter whistle-blower ap=
peared: Peiter =E2=80=9CMudge=E2=80=9D Zatko, a former security executive a=
t Twitter, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2888407=
0.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2FzaGluZ3RvbnBvc3QuY29tL3RlY2hub2xvZ3kvaW50ZXJhY3=
RpdmUvMjAyMi90d2l0dGVyLXdoaXN0bGVibG93ZXItc2VjLXNwYW0vP2l0aWQ9aHAtdG9wLXRhY=
mxlLW1haW4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4a1faf7b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">went public claiming<=
/a> that Twitter was doing various bad security things in fraudulent ways, =
being cavalier with user data and violating agreements with the Federal Tra=
de Commission and concealing information from its board of directors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked about this last week, and <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjMvYW1jLWdvZXMtYXB=
lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT=
1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDgyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB729c8ef5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I noted</a> that Zatko confirms that =
Twitter is right and Musk is wrong about their central <em>contractual </em=
>dispute: Zatko agrees with Twitter=E2=80=99s estimates that fewer than 5% =
of its mDAUs are spam bots; he just thinks that Twitter should be doing a b=
etter job of fighting spam accounts that it=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<=
/em>count as mDAUs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the broader point is that Zatko=E2=80=99s =
claims can help Musk, because he alleges <em>intentional fraud=C2=A0</em>at=
 Twitter that Musk=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0know about</em>. The schema=
tic form of Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint is (1) Twitter was doing very bad sec=
urity practices, (2) those practices created potentially disastrous risks (=
of legal liability, of lost business, of regulatory fines, etc.) for Twitte=
r,=C2=A0(3) Twitter was lying to the public about those risks, and (4)=C2=
=A0its executives were doing that intentionally in order to keep their jobs=
 and bonuses. =E2=80=9CNever mind the stuff about the bots,=E2=80=9D Musk c=
ould argue; =E2=80=9CI was tricked into buying this company that was just a=
 crater of liability because they were lying about their security practices=
.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is potentially a better argument than the=
 stuff about the bots, because:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The claims come from a respected hack=
er who was an executive at Twitter and ought to know, whereas the bot stuff=
 is just something that Musk made up with no evidence.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">It sounds bad? =E2=80=9CMudge Discovers Egregious Defi=
ciencies, Negligence, Willful Ignorance, and Threats to National Security &=
amp; Democracy,=E2=80=9D is a section header in Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint. =
If you want to get out of a deal because Twitter hid bad stuff from you, =
=E2=80=9CThreats to National Security=E2=80=9D does sound like bad stuff.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Musk=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>say he =
relied on it. One problem with Musk=E2=80=99s claims about the bots is that=
 Musk went around=C2=A0<em>before </em>the deal complaining about how Twitt=
er had too many bots and how he was the one to get rid of them. So when he =
tried to get out of the deal by saying =E2=80=9CI had no idea how many bots=
 there were, Twitter deceived me,=E2=80=9D it was very obvious from his own=
 prior statements <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjItMDUtMTcvZWxvbi1tdXNrLWRvZXMtbm90LWNhcmUtYWJvdXQtc3BhbS1ib3RzP2NtcGlkPU=
JCRDA4MjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0d=
GVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDgyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cCf1fec863" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> that he was lying</a>. But if he says now =E2=80=
=9CI had no idea what a threat Twitter was to national security,=E2=80=9D t=
hat seems more reasonable. It never came up!=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So of course Musk is going to <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubn=
l0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMi8wOC8yOS9idXNpbmVzcy9lbG9uLW11c2stdHdpdHRlci13aGlzdGxlL=
WJsb3dlci5odG1sP3NtaWQ9dHctc2hhcmU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBad49a7a9" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">try to pivot from the bot stuff to the security stuff</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elon Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers have subpoenaed Tw=
itter=E2=80=99s former security chief, Peiter Zatko, they disclosed in a co=
urt filing Monday, signaling that Mr. Musk may try to use Mr. Zatko=E2=80=
=99s accusations of false statements and security shortcomings at Twitter a=
s part of his attempt to break off an agreement he made to buy the social m=
edia company for $44 billion. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Musk adopting Mr. Zatko=E2=80=99s claims c=
ould represent a turning point in the litigation over the Twitter deal. Mr.=
 Musk would need the court=E2=80=99s permission to amend his countersuit ag=
ainst Twitter and the presiding judge, Kathaleen St. J. McCormick of the De=
laware court, may be reluctant to do so, given that the trial is relatively=
 soon.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another option for Mr. Musk would be to bring =
a federal securities fraud lawsuit against Twitter, arguing that he has the=
 right to walk away from the deal under laws governing the sale of securiti=
es. Mr. Musk could argue that Mr. Zatko=E2=80=99s concerns should have been=
 disclosed in Twitter=E2=80=99s latest annual report, a point Mr. Musk=E2=
=80=99s attorney, Alex Spiro, alluded to in a hearing last week in Delaware=
.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly9ueXBvc3QuY29tLzIwMjIvMDgvMjYvZWxv=
bi1tdXNrLXRvLWRvdWJsZS1kb3duLW9uLWRlbGF5aW5nLXR3aXR0ZXItdHJpYWwtc291cmNlcy8=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBee4630ff" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the New York Post reports</a>:<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elon Musk is expected to seize on the Twitter =
whistleblower=E2=80=99s accusations in an attempt to buy more time in his l=
egal battle with the social media company, sources closely following the si=
tuation told The Post.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk will either revise his current countersui=
t against Twitter or open up a second front with a new lawsuit after Twitte=
r=E2=80=99s former security chief Peiter =E2=80=9CMudge=E2=80=9D Zatko alle=
ged the company hid serious security problems, the sources said.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In either scenario, Musk will ask for extra ti=
me to conduct discovery on the whistleblower=E2=80=99s claims and push back=
 the five-day trial slated to begin Oct. 17 as the billionaire seeks to get=
 out of the $44 billion deal, according to sources.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So now Musk=E2=80=99s fight with Twitter is a =
fraud case. I still don=E2=80=99t love his chances. Ann Lipton, the expert =
on this topic, has a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9hbm5tbGlwdG9uL3N0YXR1cy8xNTYz=
OTA4NTcyNzY5MDI2MDQ5P3M9MTEmdD1hTWVNbXYzVTJORmlCc01vcXlma2tn/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB84d59cfd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> good Twitter thread</a> and <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly9sYXdwcm=
9mZXNzb3JzLnR5cGVwYWQuY29tL2J1c2luZXNzX2xhdy8yMDIyLzA4L2ktZ3Vlc3MtaW0td3Jpd=
GluZy1hYm91dC10d2l0dGVyLWFnYWluLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB808dc969" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> blog post</a> about the legal analysis here, which I will summarize=
 by saying (1) the bar for proving fraud is pretty high and (2) a court is =
going to be pretty annoyed by Musk=E2=80=99s opportunistic pivot to a total=
ly different legal theory.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still. I guess there are two ways to tell this=
 story. Here=E2=80=99s one:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Twitter and Musk signed a merger agre=
ement for him to buy Twitter for $44 billion.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">The stock market went down and Musk got cold feet.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So he manufactured a transparently silly excus=
e (bots) to get out of the deal, and more or less explicitly conveyed =E2=
=80=9CI am the richest person in the world and I love getting in legal figh=
ts, so if you sue to hold me to my deal I will waste a lot of time and thro=
w everything I can against you.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">Twitter sued.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Musk is rich =
and pugnacious and is very publicly hunting for stories of fraud at Twitter=
. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28884070.272571/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjMvYW1=
jLWdvZXMtYXBlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdX=
RtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDgyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzd=
HVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC729c8ef5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  The incentives are obv=
ious</a>. So a story of fraud materialized =E2=80=94=C2=A0in the form of Za=
tko=E2=80=99s somewhat miscellaneous complaints about Twitter=E2=80=99s sec=
urity practices =E2=80=94=C2=A0and now Musk can use it to try to amend his =
existing lawsuit, file new lawsuits, stretch out discovery, delay things an=
d generally make life more annoying for Twitter, as everyone expected him t=
o do. And next week maybe there=E2=80=99ll be a new whistle-blower complain=
t, and a new subpoena, a new reason to delay, etc.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s the other:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ditto</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">Ditto</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ditto</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ditto</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>
<em>Entirely by coincidence </em>it came out that Twitter was doing a big f=
raud, and Musk just got super lucky that the fraud was caught before he had=
 to close the deal.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I feel like the first story is much more plaus=
ible but the second is not <em>literally impossible</em>. If it <em>did </e=
m>turn out that Twitter was a massive secret fraud, it would hardly be fair=
 to make Elon Musk buy it, even if his efforts to get out of buying it=C2=
=A0<em>so far</em>=C2=A0have been pretty silly.</p>
