1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwODI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB94a18825" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked on Thursday</a> about a =
paper titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/28884070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2F=
ic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQxODkyMzk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd4596086" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">The =E2=80=98Actual Retail Price=E2=80=99 of Equity Tr=
ades</a>,=E2=80=9D by Christopher Schwarz, Brad Barber, Xing Huang, Philipp=
e Jorion and Terrance Odean. The paper finds that different retail brokerag=
es execute orders for the same amount of the same stock at the same time at=
=C2=A0<em>different prices</em>, and that some brokers consistently provide=
 better prices than others. But this is not correlated with how much paymen=
t for order flow each broker receives: Some brokers that accept lots of pay=
ment for order flow do better than some brokers who accept none, and vice v=
ersa.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which leaves a mystery. These brokers send the=
ir customers=E2=80=99 orders to wholesalers, electronic market-makers that =
compete to fill the orders. The wholesalers systematically give better exec=
ution=C2=A0prices to some brokers than others, but it has nothing to do wit=
h how much they are paying those brokers for those orders. But the professo=
rs don=E2=80=99t explain what does cause the difference.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The explanation that I proposed on Thursday wa=
s basically: Different retail brokers have different sorts of customers, an=
d those different customer bases might be more or less profitable for marke=
t-makers. A retail brokerage whose customers are semiprofessional, who make=
 relatively informed=C2=A0trades in relatively large size, will be less pro=
fitable for a market maker than one whose customers put in small random ord=
ers. So a market maker who notices that one brokerage has smarter bigger or=
ders will charge that brokerage=E2=80=99s customers more (offer them less p=
rice improvement) than a brokerage with dumber smaller orders. The best-per=
forming brokerage, on this measure, will be the one with the worst-performi=
ng=C2=A0<em>customers</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I like this explanation, because I think it is=
 initially surprising yet=C2=A0pleasingly intuitive, and also probably true=
. There is a prior literature. In 2001, Robert Battalio, Robert Jennings an=
d Jamie Selway <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/288=
84070.272571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWNzdS5idWZmYWxvLmVkdS9-a2VlY2h1bmcvTUdGNzQzL1=
JlYWRpbmdzL1RoZSUyMHBvdGVudGlhbCUyMGZvciUyMGNsaWVudGVsZSUyMHByaWNpbmcucGRm/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB87d28c31" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">published a paper</a> finding th=
at =E2=80=9Cbroker identity may allow market makers to differentiate betwee=
n customers when pricing market-making services,=E2=80=9D because, effectiv=
ely, some retail brokers=E2=80=99 customer bases are better at trading than=
 others=E2=80=99. If you are buying order flow from good traders, you shoul=
d charge higher spreads than you charge the=C2=A0bad traders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said, a couple of people emailed and <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28884070.272571/aHR0cH=
M6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9MdWtlS293YWxjenlrL3N0YXR1cy8xNTYyODcyMTYyODk3NTEwNDAw/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBab34438c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> tweeted</a> a different propose=
d=C2=A0explanation for the result in the paper.<a class=3D"footnote-index" =
href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: =
inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Here, the professors sent orders to buy $100 worth of stock simul=
taneously to five different retail brokers (six, if you consider their two =
different Interactive Brokers accounts separately), and they systematically=
 got different results, with some brokers regularly getting better executio=
ns than others. You could tell a story like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They put these orders in more or less=
 simultaneously (using the application programming interfaces at each broke=
rage, or pressing the buttons on the brokerage=E2=80=99s website).</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The brokerages then took different amounts=
 of time to process these orders and send them to market makers: Some broke=
rages have slower APIs, slower websites, slower routers, more complicated o=
rder-checking procedures, etc., so they take longer to send their orders to=
 market makers.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So the market make=
rs systematically=C2=A0<em>receive=C2=A0</em>orders from Brokerage A first,=
 then Brokerage B, then Brokerage C, etc., if you put the orders in all at =
the same time.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In general, when a =
market maker gets an order to buy $100 of a stock, it will fill it at the b=
est available price. If it gets another order to buy $100 of the same stock=
 a millisecond later, it will fill it at a slightly worse price: In general=
, prices=C2=A0<em>move=C2=A0</em>in response to demand, and as more orders =
come in to buy the same stock the price will go up.<a class=3D"footnote-ind=
ex" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displ=
ay: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Because the professors =
are sending six separate orders to buy the same stock at almost the same ti=
me, the first to execute will always get the best price and the last will g=
et the worst.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If true, this=C2=A0<=
em>is=C2=A0</em>a sort of evaluation of the brokerages=E2=80=99 performance=
: The =E2=80=9Cbest=E2=80=9D one does execute orders a bit faster than the =
=E2=80=9Cworst=E2=80=9D one.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But i=
t doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>matter=C2=A0</em>to any actual retail investors:=
 In general, you are not sending six separate orders on six separate platfo=
rms, so this doesn=E2=80=99t affect you. Tiny differences in latency among =
platforms don=E2=80=99t matter if no one else is racing you=C2=A0to send or=
ders at the exact same time, and if you are a normal retail investor they a=
bsolutely aren=E2=80=99t.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think this is the explanation,=
 and the authors explicitly reject it:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Given the importance of latency on=
 our results, we examine the submission time differences as well as the exe=
cution time differences of our trades for each broker pair. Table AII in Ap=
pendix A describes the distributions of differences in submission and execu=
tion times for=C2=A0pairs of brokers. Each broker pair has trades in almost=
 perfectly random order. Most of the trades are within one second of each o=
ther. Also, the median execution time differences are essentially zero. Thu=
s, no broker has any systematic advantage in terms of submission and execut=
ion times.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I mention it here because several people p=
roposed it, and it=E2=80=99s interesting.</p>
